ation Scare. Russia=E2=80=99s invasion to have =E2=80=98enormous impact=E2=
=80=99 on world food supplies. Russian Prosecutors Warn Western Companies o=
f Arrests, Asset Seizures. The Big Four face a fraught exit from Russia. Cr=
ypto Aims to Boost Influence With Washington Hires. Steve Cohen=E2=80=99s P=
oint72 to Redeem $750 Million From Hedge Fund  Melvin.=C2=A0Russian Billion=
aires Reshape Their Fortunes  While They Can. Tencent Faces Possible Record=
 Fine for Anti-Money-Laundering Violations. Former Temple Business-School D=
ean Gets Prison Term in Rankings Scandal. Grimes is dating leaker Chelsea M=
anning after Elon Musk breakup. Sanctions Ensnare Roman Abramovich Rent Pay=
ments to Queen Elizabeth.=C2=A0Elon Musk Challenges Vladimir Putin to =E2=
=80=98Single Combat=E2=80=99 for Ukraine.If you'd like to get=C2=A0Money=C2=
=A0Stuff=C2=A0in handy email form, right in your inbox, please=C2=A0subscri=
be at this link. Or you can subscribe to Money Stuff and other great Bloomb=
erg newsletters here. Thanks![1] You might! Nickel futures are physically s=
ettled, so you *could* deliver nickel (if you=E2=80=99re short) or take del=
ivery (if you're long).=C2=A0[2] That hedge fund =E2=80=94 Elliott Manageme=
nt =E2=80=94=C2=A0actually had more success blocking Argentina=E2=80=99s ex=
ternal financing by litigating the =E2=80=9Cpari passu=E2=80=9D clause in i=
ts bonds. Robin Wigglesworth wrote last week about how Russia is theoretica=
lly open to the same vulnerability. But=C2=A0this still requires hard-nosed=
 litigation against Vladimir Putin, and Russia can=E2=80=99t really get ext=
ernal dollar financing now anyway so the pari passu litigation approach has=
 no real teeth.[3] I=E2=80=99m quoting from the ISDA EMEA DC Meeting Statem=
ent, paragraph 2, which quotes the bond contractual language. In fact the D=
C quote says =E2=80=9Cif, for reasons beyond its control, the Russian Feder=
ation is unable to make payments of principal or interest (in whole or in p=
art) in respect of the Bonds in [U.S. Dollars/Euro],=E2=80=9D etc., because=
 it is covering both dollar and euro bonds, but I have omitted the euros fo=
r clarity.[4] This is not quite right as a technical matter: CDS doesn=E2=
=80=99t care what bonds you bought it =E2=80=9Cagainst=E2=80=9D; it is an i=
ndependent instrument not directly linked to the bonds. What matters is (1)=
 what *triggers* CDS (if Russia pays rubles only on the ruble-option bonds =
there's no default and so no CDS payout) and (2) what is *deliverable* in t=
he auction to settle the CDS payout: The ruble-option bonds can=E2=80=99t b=
e delivered, which means there are fewer bonds available in the auction, wh=
ich means that the price of the bonds will be higher, which means that the =
payout on CDS will be lower, for *every* CDS holder, not just the ones who =
also own ruble-option bonds.
