n bonds and Russia decides to pay you in rubles, you might object: =E2=80=
=9CNo, see, these bonds are denominated in dollars. It says right here in t=
he bond contract that you have to pay me in dollars. If you pay me in ruble=
s you are not honoring the contract and I will sue!=E2=80=9D You could sue!=
=C2=A0It will not generally do you=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>much good? Russi=
a is a country with sovereign immunity; you might get a court judgment agai=
nst it, but you will have limited ability to=C2=A0<em>enforce=C2=A0</em>tha=
t judgment. You can=E2=80=99t foreclose on its embassies, or even on its ce=
ntral bank=E2=80=99s foreign-exchange accounts. This is particularly true b=
ecause it is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Russia? It is a nuclear power whose president h=
as a history of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27=
021110.261608/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvUG9pc29uaW5nX29mX0FsZ=
XhhbmRlcl9MaXR2aW5lbmtv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6f56bf5c" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">murderin=
g his opponents abroad</a> with polonium. When Argentina defaulted on some =
foreign debt, a hedge fund famously got a court judgment and used it to <a =
